'''Alex Jay Scott''' (born 21 August 2003) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|AFCBourn}} club [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]]. Born in [[Guernsey]], he represents the [[England national football team|England national team]].

==Club career==
===Early career===
After playing with the youth teams of [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[AFC Bournemouth]],<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cyv89v09qplo|title=Alex Scott: Who is Bournemouth & England star?|date=7 November 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Scott signed for [[Isthmian League]] side [[Guernsey F.C.|Guernsey]] at the age of 16.<ref name="Guernsey profile">{{cite web |url=https://www.guernseyfc.com/team/midfielders/alex-scott |title=Alex Scott |work=guernseyfc.com |publisher=Guernsey F.C. |accessdate=25 April 2021 |archive-date=13 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220413151313/https://www.guernseyfc.com/team/midfielders/alex-scott |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his debut for the ''Green Lions'' against [[Phoenix Sports F.C.|Phoenix Sports]] on 31 August 2019 becoming the youngest ever Guernsey player.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50458449 |title=Alex Scott: Guernsey FC teenager impresses boss Tony Vance in Sevenoaks win |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=18 November 2019 |accessdate=25 April 2021 }}</ref> Scott made 15 appearances for Guernsey before his transfer in January 2020.<ref name="Guernsey profile"/> During his time with Guernsey, Scott questioned whether he could make it as a professional player.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c8r02yepejlo|title=Bournemouth news: Alex Scott on England national team call-up|date=11 November 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

=== Bristol City ===
In December 2019, Scott signed a pre-contract agreement with [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50756586 |title=Alex Scott: Bristol City sign Guernsey midfielder |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=12 December 2019 |accessdate=25 April 2021 }}</ref> Having initially linked up with the club's academy, Scott signed his first professional contract with Bristol City in March 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/bristol-city-secure-future-teen-5064228 |last=Piercy |first=James |title=Bristol City secure future of teen talent in whirlwind week for academy playmaker |work=Bristol Post |publisher=Reach plc |date=2 March 2021 |accessdate=25 April 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56256986 |title=Alex Scott: Bristol City youngster's success shows importance of Guernsey FC, says Tony Vance |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 March 2021 |accessdate=25 April 2021 }}</ref> Scott made his professional debut with Bristol City as a starter in a 1–1 Championship draw to [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] on 7 August 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56790294 |title=Bristol City 2–3 Luton Town |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=25 April 2021 |accessdate=25 April 2021 }}</ref> After missing a crucial chance earlier on in the game against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], Scott soon went on to get his first career goal for the Robins, putting them 1–0 up on 19 October 2021 at the 39th minute mark, coming off in the 78th minute in a game that ended 2–1 to Nottingham Forest.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://guernseypress.com/sport/2021/10/21/scott-off-the-mark-for-bristol-city/ |last=Le Prevost |first=Gareth |title=Scott off the mark for Bristol City |work=Guernsey Press |date=21 October 2021 |accessdate=6 November 2021 |archive-date=6 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211106165159/https://guernseypress.com/sport/2021/10/21/scott-off-the-mark-for-bristol-city/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Scott's impressive performances across the [[2022–23 Bristol City F.C. season|2022–23 season]] did not go unnoticed with manager [[Nigel Pearson]] valuing him at over £25 million amid interest from a number of [[Premier League]] clubs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bristolworld.com/sport/football/bristol-city/nigel-pearson-makes-ps25million-admission-over-bristol-city-stars-valuation-and-makes-england-claim-4060465|title='More than £25million' – Bristol City boss' warning to Spurs, West Ham and Wolves|publisher=Bristol World|last1=Dixon|first1=Joe|date=11 March 2023|accessdate=15 March 2023}}</ref> He was awarded the [[EFL Young Player of the Month]] award for February 2023 having played a starring role in Bristol City's midfield as they climbed the table.<ref name="Feb23 YPOTM">{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2023/march/alex-scott-scoops-efls-young-player-of-the-month-for-february/|title=Alex Scott scoops EFL's Young Player of the Month for February|website=EFL.com|date=15 March 2023|accessdate=15 March 2023}}</ref> Following Bristol City's defeat against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the [[FA Cup]] on 28 February 2023, Scott was described by [[Pep Guardiola]] as an "unbelievable player",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/premier-league/2023/03/03/6401d43ee2704e4dae8b4613.html|title=Alex Scott: Bristol City's 'unbelievable' talent that impressed Guardiola|first=Jon|last=Prada|date=3 March 2023|accessdate=19 March 2023|website=Marca}}</ref> and by [[Jack Grealish]] as a "top, top talent".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4302224/2023/03/16/alex-scott-bristol-city-wolves-leeds-tottenham/|url-access=subscription|title=Bristol City's Alex Scott – Everything Everywhere All At Once|first1=Nancy|last1=Frostick|first2=Thom|last2=Harris|website=The Athletic|date=16 March 2023|access-date=19 March 2023}}</ref> Scott was named [[EFL Awards|EFL Championship Young Player of the Season]], and included in the EFL Championship Team of the Season,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Follow the EFL Awards 2023 live! |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2023/april/follow-the-efl-awards-2023-live/ |access-date=23 April 2023 |website=www.efl.com |language=en-gb}}</ref> and was also named Bristol City's Player of the Year and Young Player of the Year.<ref name="POTY2223">{{cite news |url=https://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/all-the-winners-from-the-city-awards-dinner/|title=🏆 All the winners from the City awards dinner|publisher=Bristol City FC|date=6 May 2023|access-date=6 May 2023}}</ref>

=== Bournemouth ===
On 10 August 2023, Scott completed a permanent transfer to [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], one of his old clubs at youth level, on a long-term deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/first-team/scott-signs-for-the-cherries/ |title=Scott signs for the Cherries |publisher=AFC Bournemouth |date=10 August 2023 }}</ref> Bristol City received a club-record fee, believed to be around £25 million.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Barton |first=Dave |date=10 August 2023 |title=Scott joins AFC Bournemouth |url=https://www.bcfc.co.uk/city-men-news/alex-scott-joins-afc-bournemouth/ |access-date=10 August 2023 |website=Bristol City FC |language=en-ZA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Fisher |first=Ben |date=10 August 2023 |title=Bournemouth agree £25m deal to sign Alex Scott from Bristol City |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/10/bournemouth-alex-scott-bristol-city-sign-25m |access-date=10 August 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He joined Bournemouth despite having sustained a "significant" knee injury prior to leaving Bristol City, which meant Scott did not feature for Bournemouth in the opening months of the 2023–24 season.<ref>{{Cite news |last= |first= |date=11 August 2023 |title=New signing Scott set to miss first two months of the season |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/c10z35l79dyo |access-date=19 October 2023}}</ref>

Scott made his debut for the Cherries on 21 October 2023, playing 56 minutes in a 2–1 defeat to [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]. Scott then suffered an [[Medial collateral ligament|MCL]] injury four games later versus [[Manchester City F.C|Manchester City]] which kept him on the sidelines for another seven weeks. It was the end of April 2024 before he started successive Premier League games, with Bournemouth eventually finishing 12th in their first season under [[Andoni Iraola]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c2e4gjg3y07o |title=Scott ready to push for regular starts
 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 July 2024 }}</ref>

In the [[2024–25 Premier League|2024–25 Premier League season]], Scott did not complete a full 90 minutes for Bournemouth, often being utilised as a substitute. He suffered a Meniscus tear in October, requiring surgery, which kept him out for four months. On return to full fitness for the [[2025–26 Premier League|2025–26 season]], Scott regained his place in the starting eleven, featuring in each of the opening games. He scored his first goal of the season on 13 September against Brighton, in a 2–1 victory.

==International career==
Scott received his first call-up to the [[England national under-18 football team]] side in March 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://guernseypress.com/sport/2021/03/19/guernsey-footballer-alex-scott-named-in-england-u18-squad/ |title=Guernsey footballer Alex Scott named in England U18 squad |work=Guernsey Press |date=19 March 2021 |accessdate=25 April 2021 }}</ref> On 29 March 2021, Scott made his debut as a second-half substitute in England's 2–0 win against [[Wales national under-18 football team|Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2021/mar/29/wales-mu18s-0-2-england-mu18s-match-report-20210329|title=Two second-half goals seal win for England men's under-18s over Wales in Cardiff|first=Tom|last=Dean|date=29 March 2021|accessdate=25 April 2021|website=The Football Association}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2021-03-29/guernsey-footballer-alex-scott-makes-england-under-18s-debut-against-wales |title=Guernsey footballer Alex Scott makes England under 18s debut against Wales |work=itv.com |date=29 March 2021 |accessdate=25 April 2021 }}</ref>

On 2 September 2021, Scott made his debut for the [[England national under-19 football team|England U19s]] during a 2–0 victory over [[Italy national under-19 football team|Italy U19s]] at [[St George's Park National Football Centre|St. George's Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2021/Sep/02/20210209-england-mu19s-2-0-italy-report|title=England MU19s 2–0 Italy|first=Nicholas|last=Veevers|date=2 September 2021|accessdate=3 September 2021|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref> On 17 June 2022, Scott was included in the England U19 squad for the [[2022 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2022/Jun/17/england-mu19s-squad-named-for-UEFA-U19-EURO-in-Slovakia-20221706|title=Ian Foster has picked his 21-strong squad for this month's UEFA U19 EURO Finals in Slovakia|first=Frank|last=Smith|date=17 June 2022|accessdate=18 June 2022|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref> He came off the bench during the semi-final against [[Italy national under-19 football team|Italy]] to score an equalizer with his first touch of the game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/jun/28/england-italy-european-under-19-championship-semi-final-match-report|title=Scott and Quansah sink Italy and put England into Euro Under-19 final|work=The Guardian|date=28 June 2022|access-date=13 July 2022}}</ref> Scott started in the final as England won the tournament with a 3–1 extra time victory over [[Israel national under-19 football team|Israel]] on 1 July 2022.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/under19/news/0277-1585addeb047-8422a993d714-1000--israel-1-3-england-aet-chukwuemeka-and-ramsey-the-extra-time-he/|title=Israel 1–3 England (aet): Chukwuemeka and Ramsey the extra-time heroes as Young Lions fight back|website=[[UEFA]] |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |first=Sam|last=Honeyman|date=1 July 2022 |access-date=19 November 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2022/Jul/01/england-mu19s-v-israel-uefa-u19-euro-final-match-report-20220107|title=England win U19 EURO title after 3–1 win against Israel|first=Nicholas|last=Veevers|date=1 July 2022|accessdate=4 July 2022|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref>

On 21 September 2022, Scott made his [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] debut during a 3–0 victory over [[Chile national under-20 football team|Chile]] at the [[Pinatar Arena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2022/Sep/21/england-mu20s-chile-pinatar-match-report-20222109|title=Report: England MU20s 3–0 Chile|first=Liam|last=Crane|date=21 September 2022|accessdate=25 September 2022|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref> On 10 May 2023, Scott was included in the England U20 squad for the [[2023 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] and started in three of their four games at the tournament including the round of sixteen defeat against [[Italy national under-20 football team|Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/May/11/england-mu20s-squad-named-for-fifa-u20-world-cup-in-argentina-20231005|title=England MU20s squad named for World Cup in Argentina|first=Nick|last=Veevers|date=10 May 2023|accessdate=22 May 2023|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report/_/gameId/669416|title=Italy oust England at U20 World Cup thanks to late penalty|publisher=ESPN|date=1 June 2023|access-date=10 July 2023}}</ref>

On 22 March 2024, Scott made his [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] debut, coming on as a second-half substitute in a 5–1 away win against [[Azerbaijan national under-21 football team|Azerbaijan]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68639468|title=Elliott scores twice in big England U21s win|date=22 March 2024|access-date=22 March 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 6 June 2025, Scott was included in the England U21 squad for the [[2025 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] and started in five of their six games at the tournament. Scott would start in the final as England won the tournament with a 3–2 win over [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] on 28 June 2025.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cz6g18dz2dpt|title=England vs Germany LIVE: U21 Euros Final – score, radio, stats & updates |date=28 June 2025|access-date=7 November 2025|first=Nick|last=Mashiter|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 7 November 2025, Scott was called up to the [[England national football team|senior England squad]] for the first time by manager [[Thomas Tuchel]] for the squads to play Serbia and Albania, but he did not make an appearance.<ref name="auto"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12098/13465615/england-squad-phil-foden-and-jude-bellingham-return-to-thomas-tuchels-squad-as-danny-welbeck-misses-out|title=England squad: Phil Foden and Jude Bellingham return to Thomas Tuchel's squad as Danny Welbeck misses out |date=7 November 2025|access-date=7 November 2025|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

On 23 May 2026, it was announced Scott was one of five players (alongside [[Jason Steele]], [[Ethan Nwaneri]], [[Josh King (footballer, born 2007)|Josh King]] and [[Rio Ngumoha]]) that would join the [[England national football team|senior team]] for the squad's preparation camp before the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Young England talents to join Three Lions in Florida |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2026/May/22/young-england-talents-to-join-three-lions-in-florida |website=englandfootball.com |publisher=[[The Football Association]] |date=23 May 2026}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Scott is the step-brother of [[England women's national football team|England women's international]] defender [[Maya Le Tissier]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sharpe |first=Katharine |date=7 November 2025 |title=Alex Scott: Why does Guernsey-born footballer play for England? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c867y6dpy2vo |access-date=9 November 2025 |website=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> They both trained and played together in [[Saint Martin, Guernsey]], when they were teenagers and remain close friends.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Scott |first=Alex |date=26 June 2025 |title=Young Lions EURO finalist Alex Scott recalls his grassroots journey |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/May/23/alex-scott-grassroots-story-20230523 |website=The FA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=29 September 2025 |title=Alex Scott: Bournemouth midfielder targets senior England call-up |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/czxw982jr9yo |access-date=9 November 2025 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Scott was named 2024 Channel Islands Sports Personality of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.islandfm.com/news/guernsey/alex-scott-wins-ci-sports-personality-of-the-year/|title=Alex Scott Wins CI Sports Personality Of The Year|publisher=Island FM|date= 9 February 2024|accessdate=24 December 2025}}</ref>

